metadata.title: Ryan Navion
aws::graph::propositions: Ryan Navion Aircraft Variants
25+ Ryan Navion aircraft were built.
X-16 Bi-Navion was a twin-engined prototype.
X-16 Bi-Navion was designed by Dauby Equipment Company.
X-16 Bi-Navion was built by Dauby Equipment Company in 1952.
X-16 Bi-Navion had two 130hp Lycoming engines.
X-16 Bi-Navion production was handled by Riley.
X-16 Bi-Navion production was later handled by Temco.
Temco Riley 55 was the initial version of the twin engined Navion conversion.
D-16 Twin Navion was the production version of the X-16.
D-16 Twin Navion had two 150hp Lycoming O-320 engines.
D-16 Twin Navion had strengthened wings.
Riley performed 19 D-16 Twin Navion conversions.
Temco performed 46 D-16 Twin Navion conversions.
Temco D-16A was an improved D-16 conversion.
Temco D-16A had two 170hp Lycoming O-340-A1A engines.
Temco D-16A had nacelle tanks.
Temco D-16A had 20 gallon tip tanks on each wing.
Temco D-16A had 144 gallons of fuel capacity total.
Temco performed 45 D-16A conversions.

text:
25+- built.
X-16 Bi-Navion
One twin-engined (130hp Lycomings) prototype designed and built by Dauby Equipment Company in 1952, production by Riley and later by Temco.
Temco Riley 55
Initial version of the twin engined Navion conversion.
D-16 Twin Navion
Production version of the X-16 with two 150hp Lycoming O-320 engines and strengthened wings, 19 conversions by Riley and 46 by Temco.
Temco D-16A
Improved D-16 conversion with two 170hp Lycoming O-340-A1A engines, nacelle tanks and 20 gallon each tip tanks, 144 gallons fuel total. 45 conversions.
